How to Create a Text Network
Creating a text network poses some unique challenges.
First, we have to deal with the two-mode nature of the most common
input matrix: the DTM.
Second, we have to deal with particularly high network density.
Today, were going to focus simply on how to create a text network
from a DTM while keeping these two issues in mind. Next week well
talk about some of the various analyses we can carry out once we
have a properly constructed text network.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 27, 2019 3 / 28
How to Create a Text Network
The main package well use today is called textnets (Bail 2018a).
A lot of todays code comes from/is inuenced by Bail (2018b, n.d.)
and Murphy and Knapp (n.d.).
Well start by thinking about the two-mode nature of DTMs. Well
then talk about how to handle high network density in text networks.
Finally, well see how useful the textnets package is for handling
these issues and streamlining text network construction.

Two-Mode Networks
A DTM is an example of what we refer to as a two-mode networkalso
known as an aliation network.
Figure 3: Sample of the cleaned and lemmatized SOTU DTM
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 27, 2019 8 / 28
The rows and columns are dierent elements in a two-mode network.
In the case of a DTM, we have words (columns) distributed across
documents (rows).
Lets take a look at the DTM in graph form. We often refer to this as a
bipartite graph when in graph form and as a incidence matrix when in
matrix form. Run the code from where you dene corpus.net down to
the rst plot() function.

The Issue
Typically, though, we want to focus on the relations between documents
given their similarities in word usage, or the relationship between words
given the documents they tend to co-occur within.
So what do we do?

From an Incidence Matrix to an Adjacency Matrix
We can use a bit of matrix algebra to get the one-mode projections of
the two-mode network. In other words, we can turn the incidence matrix
into two adjacency matrices: a document-by-document matrix and a
word-by-word matrix.
Heres how we do it:
D = AA
T
(1)
For the document-by-document matrix, D, and:
D = A
T
A (2)
for the word-by-word matrix, W.

Weighting
Typically, our DTM wont be binarized like this. The DTM will usually be
weighted either by the term frequency or tf-idf scores.
Luckily, the same rules apply for getting the one-mode projections.
tf-idf scores are the norm for text networks (Bail 2016), since we typically
want to connect together those documents with similarly distinctive
language.
In the case of a one-mode document-by-document projection from tf-idf
scores, the edge between documents i and j is the sum of the tf-idf scores
between the terms in those documents that they share in common (Bail
2016:11828).
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 27, 2019 18 / 28
The Problem of Network Density
One issue that youll likely have noticed is that we had to remove some
edges in order to make our graphs interpretable.
This is because text networks tend be very dense: that is, any given
vertex is very likely to be tied to almost every other vertex to some degree.
We typically handle this by removing some of edges with smaller weights.
This translates to removing ties between documents that have only weak
overlap in word usage (or removing ties between words that co-occur only
a handful of times across documents).
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 27, 2019 19 / 28
The textnets Package
Luckily, the textnets package handles most of this work.
First, well use the PrepText() function to simultaneously group together
speeches by president and take care of a little preprocessing. Well also
specify that we want the group-by-group matrix (same as
document-by-document, since the grouping variable just appends each
speech to one another by president).
Well repeat that function, but this time specifying that we want the
word-by-word matrix (with node type = "groups").
The function automatically removes weak edges using a network
backbone technique (Bail 2018).
Dont bother trying to run these functions in class. Theyll take a while.
Everything should already be loaded in your global environment.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 27, 2019 20 / 28
For the document network:
sotu . docs . net <- PrepText ( corpus ,
groupvar = " President " ,
textvar = " texts " , node _ type = " groups " ,
tokenizer = " words " , remove _ stop _ words = TRUE ,
remove _ numbe rs = T)
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 27, 2019 21 / 28

We can give the space between vertices a bit more meaning by using what
is referred to as the Fruchterman-Reingold force-directed spacing
algorithm (Fruchterman and Reingold 1991). Essentially, this algorithm
arranged vertices so that vertices that have stronger associations are
drawn together and those that dont are repelled apart.
Unfortunately, textnets does not currently allow you to specify this
layout. So I made a modied version of the VisTextNet() function,
which is in VisTextNet2.R. Run that R script, then run this to apply
Fruchterman-Reingold:
VisTe xtNet2 ( docs . network )
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 March 27, 2019 24 / 28
Document Network with FR
The closer the two vertices, the stronger their speech overlap. You also
get a better sense of the clustering solution that is automatically
generated with CreateTextnet(). Again, your layout may look dierent.

Conclusion

graphs.

down, well devote next week to exploring some of the techniques we can
use to explore the formal properties of these text networks.
